{"cursor":"3139","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n\n'Francis Ruddle' (23 November 17989 February 1882) was a 19th-century master\nbuilder and carpenter, born and based in Peterborough. His carpentry work\nincludes the current choir stalls in place at Westminster Abbey in London.\n\nRuddle carried out much of his work in association with a local Peterborough\nbuilder, John Thompson, with whom he had a long-term business relationship,\neventually combining to form the company Ruddle & Thompson. After the death\nof John Thompson, Ruddle worked alongside his late partner's son, John\nThompson (junior).\n\nWorking to designs of the celebrated architect and designer, Edward Blore, in\n1830-31 Ruddle fabricated new choir stalls and an organ screen for his local\nPeterborough Cathedral. Guide to Peterborough Cathedral, Ed Davy, 1846\nThe carpentry work was removed from the Cathedral in 1890 at the time that the\ncentral tower of the Cathedral was in danger of collapse. Cathedrals, Abbeys\n& Churches, T.G. Bonney, 1888 Some of the choir stalls were procured by a\nparishioner at St Dominic's Church in Newcastle upon Tyne and are still in place\nin St Dominic's today. The Buildings of England:Northumberland, Volume 15,\nby Nikolaus Pevsner et al, Penguin, 1957\n\nThe work at Westminster Abbey was carried out in two phases, again working under\nthe designs of Blore who was then engaged as Surveyor to the Abbey. A new organ\ncase, built by Ruddle in 1832-34, was removed from the Abbey in 1845. The\nOrgan & Bells of Westminster Abbey, Jocelyn Perkins, 1937 The choir stalls\nwere fabricated in 1845-48 Architectural Description of Westminster Abbey,\nH Clarke, 1851 and are still in place today.\n\nIn 1858 Ruddle & Thompson were entrusted with the role of general contractors\nfor the restoration of Hereford Cathedral under the designs of another\ncelebrated architect of the era, George Gilbert Scott. Stamford Mercury, 12\nMarch 1858\n\nIn 1863 Ruddle fabricated a new pulpit for Lincoln Cathedral for the sum of\nÂ£500, Peterborough Advertiser, 9th May 1863 again working to designs\nof George Gilbert Scott. The pulpit, which is positioned within St Hugh's Choir,\nis still in use.\n\nOther work by Ruddle during his career includes Thorpe Hall (Peterborough),\nThicket Priory, Ripon Cathedral, Queen's private chapel at Windsor Castle, All\nSaints' Church, Oakham, the chapel at Balliol College, Oxford and the former\nBritish Embassy in Constantinople (Istanbul). Obituary in Peterborough\nAdvertiser, 18 February 1882\n","linknr":114,"url":"Francis_Ruddle","recorded":1376426224,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Francis_Ruddle&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Francis_Ruddle&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Francis_Ruddle","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.rtlcite%2Cwikihiero%7Cext.uls.nojs%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.visualEditor.viewPageTarget.noscript&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=site&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=startup&only=scripts&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/geoiplookup","//meta.wikimedia.org","#mw-navigation","#p-search","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/3b/Text_document_with_page_number_icon.svg/40px-Text_document_with_page_number_icon.svg.png","/wiki/Wikipedia:Citing_sources","/wiki/Wikipedia:CITEHOW","/wiki/Wikipedia:WikiProject_Fact_and_Reference_Check","/wiki/File:Choir_pu